snippet.textDisplay: Have a similar story from sweden: Köping Uttersberg-Riddarhyttan railway originally built for 3 1/2 english feet (1067mm, a common narrow gauge.) and ordered a steam loco from a swedish manufacturer, wanting it to be built for a 3,59 swedish foot (1066mm). Comversion errors made the manufactuer making a loco being 3,59 english feet (1094mm). It was too expensive for the railway to correct the loco, so they made the railway and wagons 3,59 feet wide instead. It closed down in 1969, but alot of the rolling stock and part of the railway still exist. I belive there is an ambition to revive it as a heritage railway...

snippet.textDisplay: The same happened in Czechia when buying new trams (streetcars). There are basically two norms. One for building tracks and stops and another norm for vehicles. Each has their own clearances. Everything was fine, went along for decades, until low floor trams came to be. Suddenly, there was an overlap which nobody noticed before. Solution? Trim the trams, as only the covers of the bogies were affected. Simply cut them a bit out and everything was fine again. True story.

snippet.textDisplay: Hi ! In fact, RFF and SNCF knew exaclty the problem when the trains was bought. Making some work to have all stations respecting the standard size should have been done, and that would be completly stupid to not invest 70 millions on an investment of 20 billions of trains that will last for at least 30 years.The polemic started just because RFF and the SNCF was arguing about who must pay for that. This is an infrastructure investment, so, for the SNCF, it should be RFF, but it's the SNCF that chose those new trains, so for RFF, it should be SNCF.This dispute is a good example of the big issues we have since the SNCF is splited in two part (and now it's worse).Another "fun" example was few years ago, when a TGV broke down in the middle of nowhere. Passenger spent more than 20 hours in the train for a ~3 hours trip. There was many issue during the rescue that can explain that. But few hours after the breakdown, a fret train was passing nearby and the conductor offered to tow the TGV. The answer was a clear no, because the fret train are handled by SNCF Fret while the TGV was handled by SNCF mobilités.

snippet.textDisplay:
To be honest after laughing for a bit I now think it wasn't a bad thing. Funny ? Sure. But think about it a bit. The whole "mistake" costed less than 0.3% of the program. It wasn't much. Furthermore I can totally see the "right width trains" cost way more then that.
Also at the end French got swider aka more comfortable trains (20cm doesn't seem like much but since corridor width etc is fixed due to safety regulations it actually means 4cm wider seats - which DOES make a difference - ask airlines lol).

Overall if the numbers from video add up (can't check it now) the whole thing was a GOOD thing for French.

Now for more funny and costly mistake due to actual miscommunication between government (navy) agencies is the Iowa class battleship case. AFTER they almost finished them they found out that due to miscommunication they had wrong dimensions and the guns don't fit inside turrets. Trust me it was way more expensive to design a whole new gun just to fix that :)
